# ============================================
# Railway Environment Variables Template
# ============================================
# Set these in your Railway service settings.
# Railway auto-provides PORT — do not set it manually.
#
# DEPLOYMENT: 4 services from same repo (monorepo)
#   1. Backend      → root directory: backend/
#   2. Dashboard    → root directory: dashboard/
#   3. WhatsApp Bot → root directory: whatsapp-bot/
#   4. PWA          → root directory: pwa/ (Dockerfile deploy)
#
# Plus 2 plugins: PostgreSQL + Redis

# === Backend Service (root: backend/) ===
# DATABASE_URL=${{Postgres.DATABASE_URL}}
# REDIS_URL=${{Redis.REDIS_URL}}
# NODE_ENV=production
# JWT_SECRET=<generate-a-strong-secret>
# SERVICE_KEY=<shared-secret-between-services>
# GROQ_API_KEY=<your-groq-api-key>
# SQUAD_BASE_URL=https://sandbox-api-d.squadco.com
# SQUAD_SECRET_KEY=<your-squad-secret-key>
# SQUAD_PUBLIC_KEY=<your-squad-public-key>
# SQUAD_WEBHOOK_SECRET=<your-webhook-secret>
# SQUAD_MERCHANT_ID=<your-merchant-id>
# WEBHOOK_BASE_URL=https://<backend-service>.up.railway.app

# === Dashboard Service (root: dashboard/) ===
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://<backend-service>.up.railway.app
# NEXT_PUBLIC_WS_URL=wss://<backend-service>.up.railway.app/dashboard/feed
# NEXT_PUBLIC_MAPBOX_TOKEN=<your-mapbox-token>

# === WhatsApp Bot Service (root: whatsapp-bot/) ===
# BACKEND_URL=https://<backend-service>.up.railway.app
# SERVICE_KEY=<same-shared-secret-as-backend>
# ENABLE_BOT=true
# BOT_ADMIN_NUMBERS=2349137839404
#
# --- First-time pairing (headless) ---
# Set PAIRING_PHONE to your WhatsApp number (without +) for first deploy.
# Check Railway logs for the 8-digit pairing code.
# Go to WhatsApp > Settings > Linked Devices > Link with Phone Number.
# Enter the code. Once paired, REMOVE this var (session persists in auth_state/).
#
# PAIRING_PHONE=2349137839404
#
# --- Persistent session ---
# Railway resets the filesystem on each deploy. To keep the bot connected:
# Option A: Mount a volume at /app/auth_state in Railway service settings
# Option B: After first pairing locally, commit auth_state/ to a private branch
#
# Recommended: Add a Railway Volume mounted at /app/auth_state

# === PWA Service (root: pwa/, Dockerfile) ===
# Build args (set in Railway → service → Variables):
# VITE_API_URL=https://<backend-service>.up.railway.app
# VITE_MAPBOX_TOKEN=<your-mapbox-token>
#
# Note: Since PWA uses a Dockerfile build, set these as Railway Variables.
# Railway injects them as build args during docker build.
# The nginx container uses PORT env var automatically.

# ============================================
# Demo Flow (how it all connects)
# ============================================
#
# 1. Audience scans QR code on dashboard → opens WhatsApp with pre-filled message
# 2. They send a message like "sold 5 bags rice 25000"
# 3. WhatsApp Bot receives it via Baileys
# 4. Bot calls POST /api/demo/event on Backend with actor=pushName (their WhatsApp name)
# 5. Backend emits event via Redis pub/sub → WebSocket
# 6. Dashboard receives event via WebSocket → shows on map, feed, plays sound
#
# The demo can also run autonomously:
# - Dashboard "Story" button → POST /api/demo/run { scenario: "story" }
# - Backend runs pre-scripted event sequence with delays
# - Events flow to dashboard in real-time via same WebSocket pipe
